<span class=dateline>October   03, 2003</span> - It's Friday! That means we have a brand new "Ask SOE" for you today. This one features three new questions and answers with Steve "Moorgard" Danuser, the Community Manager for EverQuest II.<BR>
<BR></div></div><div id="intelliTxt"><div class="editorial">
As always, we encourage you to <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=57366059&replies=0">comment on this article</A> or just talk in general about EverQuest II on our <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/board.asp?brd=22210">EQII General Board</A>.<BR>
<BR>
Please also send me questions for this, our EQ Q&A, our Lords of EverQuest Q&A or anything else at <A HREF="mailto:lepidus@vaultnetwork.com">lepidus@vaultnetwork.com</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<B><CENTER>Ask SOE #5</B><BR>
<I>With Steve "Moorgard" Danuser, Community Manager, EQII</I></CENTER><BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> Many people loved the 1st person camera view in EQII. How customizable will the camera be in EQII?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> First person will be the default character perspective, but we intend to support all the camera angles that EverQuest does, including using the mouse wheel to pull back and give a "follow cam" perspective.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> What will the restrictions imposed on a character based on their alignment? What about the advantages?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> At the most basic level, characters are aligned to one of the two starting cities, Qeynos or Freeport. Citizens of one city will be considered enemies of the other, and the populations will react to outsiders accordingly. In other words, you won't be freely walking the streets of the opposing city.<BR>
<BR>
Players and guilds align themselves to specific factions within their home city, and their contributions determine how prominent each faction is within the world. If the Qeynos military faction is more prominent than the Freeport military, for example, all citizens of Qeynos will receive bonuses to their combat techniques. Members of the faction that is most dominant in the city will receive additional benefits. Likewise, the guild with the largest contribution to the most prominent faction will receive perks of their own, including special housing and access to lucrative tasks and valuable items.<BR>
<BR>
Faction standings will be calculated on a monthly basis, which will allow the pendulum to swing back and forth. Players and guilds can either take an active role in this competition or ignore it if they so choose; participation in this political meta-game is entirely optional.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> It is all well and good to have loads of content for small groups, but what about truly epic content? Could you give us a preview of one of the major epic encounter monsters you have planned?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> Our goal is to give players challenging content at all levels of gameplay rather than just at the high end. For example, at a relatively low level in the Commonlands players will have access to two distinct flavors of epic encounters.<BR>
<BR>
The first type is a multi-group encounter that compels players to face a large number of adversaries at once. In the heart of the Commonlands, the Bloodskull Orcs are building their forces. Four groups of adventurers will invade Bloodskull Valley and attempt to defeat the army of Overlord Grelk. The orcs will be patrolling their outpost in organized formations and will sound the alarm if they detect an invading force. Players will be involved in a coordinated effort against the orcish forces, facing over twenty adversaries at a given time. Only through the cooperation of all four groups of players can the enemy hoard be defeated, eventually leading to a confrontation with Grelk himself.<BR>
<BR>
The goal of this type of encounter is to give a feeling of a massive battle. Rather than pitting a huge raid force against mobs pulled a handful at a time, you will have a smaller but more coordinated group of players against a considerable number of opponents. Success will depend on players understanding their roles on the raid and working as a team to achieve victory.<BR>
<BR>
An example of the second type of epic encounter is found in Zarvonn's Tower. Zarvonn was once a member of the Arcane Scientists, but he was exiled for his radical views. A group of players will work their way through the tower, defeating Zarvonn's undead minions until the adventurers draw the attention of the master himself.<BR>
<BR>
This type of encounter is the good ol' fashioned dungeon crawl, where a group of adventurers works its way to the boss and his entourage. Party members will see their skills pushed to the limit, requiring every class to be played to its fullest potential.<BR>
<BR>
Both flavors of epic encounters will be available at the high end of the game, too. But you'll have to discover that content for yourself down the road.<div class=byline>-- <a href="mailto:lepidus@vaultnetwork.com">Lepidus</A></div>
	</div>
</div>
